videoTitle: California Employment Law: Two Week Notice #worklife
commentText: I used to work for an old man who would accept a two-week notice, then cut them a two-week check and walk them out the door.  His logic was that they would not be vested in the company for those two weeks or that they would do something underhanded. After he retired, the new boss would make them work the last two weeks, and after a few bad apples, he reinstated the old policy.

videoTitle: California Employment Law: Two Week Notice #worklife
commentText: I gave 2 weeks notice to the first hospital I worked for. They promptly changed the schedule to have me work 7 12-hour shifts in a row by having them straddle 2 weeks. I let them know that I was extending them a courtesy and they were taking advantage of that courtesy so I wouldn't be coming back tomorrow. They asked me if I was planning to finish my shift that day and I said yes since I was not going to be open to patient abandonment allegations.  They demanded that I come in for an exit interview before they would release my PTO. videoTitle: California Employment Law: Two Week Notice #worklife
commentText: EDIT to clarify: Yes, it is most likely, depending on the state, perfectly legal to terminate the employment. That isn't what the comment said. I said you either schedule the employee during their notice period, or you've terminated them. Employers are well within their legal right to do so. I never said they couldn't. However, at least in the state where I live and own a business, if you do not let the employee work their notice, you have fired them. In my state, not letting the employee work their notice is considered termination, without cause, and while legal, will allow them to successfully file an unemployment claim. Successful unemployment claims raise your unemployment rates. You can do it if you want, but if they file, you'll take the unemployment hit. Responders were too focused on it being legal or not, but that's not what my comment addressed. No where did I say anything about it being legal to not let an employee work their notice. People who went that direction, either can't read, or just decided to do their own comment thread, under my comment, pretending I said something I didn't say.   Original comment:  I gave you a notice of an intent to quit. I don't actually quit until my last day. You told me I wasn't welcome back as of this moment. I haven't quit yet, so either I'm welcome to come back for my shift tomorrow, or I'm fired. If I'm not fired, I'll be back tomorrow.

commentText: It's not possible to complete the full Chartered Accountancy (CA) course in just one year. The CA course, including Foundation, Intermediate, and Final levels, typically takes a minimum of 4.5 to 5 years to complete. This includes the required articleship training period of three years. Even for graduates entering through the direct entry route, the minimum duration is 4.5 years.  Here's a more detailed breakdown:  Foundation Level: 6 months Intermediate Level: 8-10 months Articleship Training: 3 years Final Level: 6-12 months While some students might be able to accelerate their studies by studying intensely, passing exams quickly, and potentially completing the final level in one year after clearing the intermediate level, this would be an exception rather than the norm. commentText: This whole minimum wage issue really blows my mind. My senior year in high school (1982) the minimum wage was $3.35 an hour. Adjusted for inflation, that would be about $11.15 today. That may not sound like a lot of money, but we weren‚Äôt supporting a family with that kind of money. That‚Äôs because those jobs were never meant to support a family!  Back in high school, I lived in a small town in the Mojave Desert where two highways connected. The town was full of fast food restaurants and gas stations which was cool because it gave all of us in high school a place to work. No one except the managers, was working at McDonald‚Äôs to raise a family. We were all working there to pay for the gas in our cars, take out our dates, buy our weed (Yes I said it), or whatever else we needed money for. That‚Äôs exactly what those jobs were for. And most of us kept those jobs until we graduated.  Perhaps the most important part of those jobs was that it taught us to be responsible. Those were important skills to learn in high school. I don‚Äôt see a lot of teenagers holding jobs anymore. What‚Äôs up with that?

videoTitle: California Employment Law #HR #job
commentText: I'm 20 years old, blind, and love working with kids. I was placed on field experience this past semester, and the higher-ups decided I'm not safe around kids. Not safe around 2-year-olds, but fine around 4-year-olds. I'm smart enough to read between the lines. Just to be clear, nothing happened with anyone's safety. No one crashed, no one got hurt. They just didn't like it when I said that I don't like being touched by adults, but I'm okay if the kids do it. I left the placement. People judge ne. They tell me that I should have told someone, that I was supposed to push through. But the way I think about it is this way: if I let these people get away with it, what grounds would I have to stand on when I'm employed in the future? What grounds would I stand on when people discriminate against me, make assumptions about me, or be disrespectful toward me for no reason other than them being in higher position than me? It's a rule I have for myself, with my family included: if you disrespect me, I walk away. I've cut off my father for years because he dared to fake his own death and test a boundary I have. No guilt-tripping worked, and I told him off. What makes people think I can't do it to literal strangers just because they're paying me is beyond me.
